President Barack Obama has proclaimed May 2012 as Asian American and Pacific Islander Heritage Month. The proclamation recognizes the significant contributions made by Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders throughout the history of the United States. It acknowledges the hardships faced by these communities, such as internment during World War II, and the ongoing challenges they still encounter, including prejudice and disparities in education, employment, housing, and healthcare. The proclamation also highlights the achievements of Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders in various fields, such as business, government, science, and the arts. The President emphasizes the importance of celebrating diversity and ensuring equal opportunities for all people in the country. He calls upon all Americans to learn about the history of Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders and participate in appropriate programs and activities during this month.